---

[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In this video, I\'m testing retail and bland in seven areas from ease of use and telefan options to latency, pricing, and hidden costs to see which is the better platform for building voice AI agents. I\'ll also link to a side-by-side comparison below with all the results,'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and you can plug in your requirements to see which tools the better fit for you. So, let\'s start with Retail AI. So, Retail AI is one of the easiest platforms to build voice agents on, particularly if you\'re a beginner. So, from their platform, you can create an'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'agent up here. Go to voice agent, and you got a few options. Now, the templates are very good in retail. Generally, I recommend starting with a conversational flow agent. This means you can build your voice agent out on a nice visual canvas. This also has some'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'benefits from a latency perspective because it means rather than sticking one gigantic prompt that is being sent with every call to the LLM, you can break your prompt out into different steps, giving your voice agent only the context that it needs at each step of'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the conversation. So, I\'ll just show you kind of how that looks. So, if we go into conversational flow agent, we\'ll create that. And I\'ll talk through a couple of kind of key features and concepts in retail as we go. So, here you can see the main visual canvas that'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you build out your voice agents on. And you can enter your prompts into any of these nodes. Then you got your different node options down the left here. So, you can add a call transfer node. We can add functions, which I\'ll touch on in a second, conversation nodes, SMS,'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'extracting variables, MCP connections, again I\'ll touch on in a moment. You enter in the prompt or a static sentence. And then you can set up your And then you can set up your transition. Then you can set up your transition.'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then you can enter here. Then you can enter. Then you enter in your transitions, which is just the kind of the possible outcome, the possible things the caller could say at that step. And then you just connect them to'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the different nodes. Then if you click into any node, you\'ve got all the options for how to configure that node. So if we go into this one for example, we\'ll see you could change the LLM it uses for example. We can add knowledge to it. We can make it a global node'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which means that the agent can decide to jump to that node at any point in the conversation. Just on that point, there\'s two different nodes for building in retail. You can either have rigid mode where it follows the flow quite precisely. This is pretty good if you'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have a very predictable conversational flow and you essentially want it to follow a script. Or you got flex mode which allows for a little bit of variability and means that if we\'re going down this path but someone suddenly mentions something that has a'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'path over here, it gives the agent the autonomy to jump between different nodes. So as you can see it\'s visually very intuitive. So let\'s touch on telefan and voice options. So the default voice engine that retail uses is 11 Labs which is the one that I would'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generally recommend. You do have a few other options like Cartisia, Miniax, OpenAI voices. But generally speaking, for most agents, you\'re likely going to want to use 11 Labs. You can also add in your own custom voice. If you\'ve paid for either an instant or a professional'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'voice on 11 Labs, you can just enter in your voice ID here from 11 Labs. Pop in an API key, then your voice agent can use your voice. You can also create a voice clone directly in inside retail. So you can drop in some audio files here'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then that will create an instant voice in 11 Labs. So, I\'ll play you an example in a moment of a voice agent I\'ve actually built. If we go back out of here, I\'ll just touch on Telefan while we\'re out here as well. So, retail do make it pretty easy to connect phone'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'numbers to your agent and you can buy them from within the platform. So, phone numbers cost $2 a month. Now, slight downside here. If you are outside the US and Canada, you\'ll need to import your phone numbers either via Twilio or Telnix or Zip Trunk, but it\'s pretty'

[03:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'straightforward. It takes literally a couple of minutes to get a phone number and verify it and you can then connect it to one of your agents. This, by the way, works for both inbound and outbound agents. So, you can either have people call that number or you can make calls'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from that number. So, let\'s just jump into one of these agents and I\'ll show you a quick example of the voice realism. So, let\'s go into this dental outbound agent. So, one of my favorite things about retail is testing. Some'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'voice AI tools, you have to actually have it call your mobile device, which racks up costs and credits, and it\'s also just a bit clunky to keep doing that. Whereas, retail make it really easy. You can just click test agent and you can either chat with your agent,'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is kind of handy if you\'re in a public place and you don\'t want to look insane having this conversation back and forth with your agent, or you can test the audio and you literally just click. &gt;&gt; Hi, this is Grace from South Bay Dental Office. I\'m reaching out regarding the form you submitted to learn more about'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'our teeth cleaning package. Am I speaking with Marcus? &gt;&gt; Yes, &gt;&gt; I\'m following up to see if you\'re still interested in our teeth cleaning package. &gt;&gt; No, I\'m all good. Thank you. So, as you can see, really simple, and it\'s nice'

[04:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that it visually kind of shows you which step of your workflow it\'s going down, so you can make sure that it\'s going through all those routes as you would expect. The voice quality also pretty good. That was using Simo, which is just the default 11 Labs options, but there\'s tons of different options that you can'

[04:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'choose from here. So, let\'s touch on one of the things that is less good about retail integrations. So, retail, of course, if you are technical, you can connect this to absolutely anything using web hooks or using model context protocol. But if you are nontechnical,'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your options are a bit more limited. Retail don\'t have much in the way of native integrations. So if you want to connect it to something, you can add a function. And cow.com is basically the only native integration you will find on'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'retail.com. What I would say is that cow.com is kind of a bridge between various different calendar software. So if you want to connect retail to Google calendar or outlet calendar, for example, you can connect those into'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cow.com. So, this is sort of like a Google calendar integration, albeit indirectly. But that is it of anything other than a calendar integration. You\'re going to need to get your hands dirty either by building a custom'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'function where you trigger a HTTP request or by connecting into an MCP server, which is not massively difficult. And in some ways, this means the world is your oyster because virtually every tool now has its own MCP'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'server. And all you need to do is enter the MCP server URL and then any headers or query parameters that you need to authenticate it. But I do point it out because it is a relative weakness of retail. Most voice AI tools I use have a'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much broader range of native integrations, but retail does not. So that brings me on to another point which is concurrency. So, this is an important concept when building voice agents because particularly if you\'re doing'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'outbound calls or if you have busy periods and quiet periods, if you have 10 customers all calling you at once, you don\'t want to only have one phone line. That means everyone\'s kind of on hold for ages. So, by default, you can have up to 20 concurrent calls on'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'retail, which is pretty generous. And they\'ve also got this handy feature called concurrency burst, where if you get a sudden influx of calls, instead of putting everyone on hold or forcing you to buy extra phone lines, you just pay a slightly higher rate. And this works for'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up to three times your normal limit. So essentially 60 concurrent calls. If you consistently have a higher number of concurrent calls, you\'re running a call center for example, you can of course adjust your limit and it cost $8 per additional concurrent phone line, which'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'again is pretty reasonable. So let\'s talk about latency. So the first thing I really like about retail is they make this transparent. This is not true of all voice AI platforms. So when you\'re building your voice agent, you can see'

[06:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up here in the top bar the estimated latency for your agent. And this is quite handy because it gives you an indication if you suddenly add a really massive global prompt that\'s going to push up the latency. You can also see'

[07:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things for example like changing the model either using the fast tier or something like GPT 4.1 nano. You should see an instant reduction in the latency and generally from my experience with retail it is slightly on the pessimistic'

[07:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'side. So generally I find that my actual latency is often slightly better than this. So coming on to that point, if you go into your call logs, you can see your actual latency. And another thing I really like about this is you can see'

[07:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the breakdown. So you don\'t just get this kind of one number. So here you can see 756 milliseconds, which is roughly what I see on average. So when I\'ve done standardized latency testing across different tools, I believe with retail I was getting 714 milliseconds of endtoend'

[07:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'latency. That is not the best I\'ve seen, but it is still very good. It\'s still in the realms of sounding natural and being very usable for a production voice agent. Thing I really like is that if you hover over here, you can get the'

[07:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'breakdown of where that latency is happening. So you can see is it at the speechto text stage, is it the LLM or is it at the texttospech voice engine. And this is really helpful because it tells you where the problem is and therefore what you can do to improve and optimize'

[08:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. This is quite rare to see in voice agent platforms. There\'s only one or two other platforms I can think of that actually give you this information. And for me, this just tells me like retail is not trying to hide anything. They\'re giving you this information so you can do something with it and actually make'

[08:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'your voice agent better. So in this case, for example, it\'s clear that we do not have a latency problem at the transcription stage, but we might want to tighten up our prompts or use a different model for the LLM inference and possibly we might want to have a'

[08:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'play around with the the voice engine, but big wins are going to be at the LLM stage. So just really helpful. Now let\'s touch on costs. Now, generally speaking, when you add everything up, so like the LLM cost, telefan costs, etc., retail'

[08:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'comes out around about 13 cents per minute. Now, obviously that is going to depend on the model you choose, the telefan options, there\'s dozens of things that affect this number, but'

[09:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generally for a standard tech stack, so GP4.1 deep transcription and 11 Labs Turbo V2, this is roughly going to be about right. It is not the absolute cheapest option for voice agents, but it\'s generally'

[09:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very reasonable. Anything under about 14 15 cents per minute is pretty decent. So, for me, retail is a really solid option. It gets a lot of the boring stuff like testing, latency, concurrency, it gets all these things right, but it also just makes it really'

[09:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'easy to build production quality voice agents. So, if you\'re nontechnical, if you like building in no code, and you don\'t want to be in the weeds building voice agents via an API, Retail for me is about as good as it gets. So, next up, let\'s have a look at Bland AI. So'

[09:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Bland is one of the most powerful platforms for building voice agents on. It does have a bit of a learning curve to it and I wouldn\'t recommend it to beginners, but it\'s pretty impressive how much stuff you can customize inside the bland platform. So easiest way to'

[09:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get started in bland is probably with conversational pathways. This gives you a nice kind of visual flow editor for building your agent on. So if we go into this one for example, you can see like a lot of platforms, you can build out your'

[10:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'agents on this kind of nice canvas where each part of the conversation can be represented by a node and then you can create different conditions for what to do based on how the caller responds. We can test our agent directly in the platform. So you don\'t have to hook this'

[10:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up to a phone number or have it call your phone just to test it, which is quite nice. Also, the testing functionality inside Bland is very mature. This is something that tends to set apart the good tools from the less good tools is things like having'

[10:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'evaluations and good QA features for testing your agents because this is something that kind of starts to become more and more important when you start shipping agents to production. In terms of telefan, if we go over to phone numbers, you can buy phone numbers'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'directly inside the bland platform. They are $15 a month, which is relatively expensive, and they\'re only US numbers. So, generally speaking with Bland, you would almost certainly want to bring your own Twilio, which you can do here, or you can do it via SIP trunk, but you'

[10:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need to but you\'d need to contact Bland to do that. Now, in most voice AI platforms, when you\'re building your agent, you just select the voice off of 11 Labs that you want, and you\'re kind of done. Bland AI go one step further, and I really like how they approach'

[11:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this. So, with Bland AI, you create a persona, which you then attach to your workflow or your AI voice agent. And this just gives you a lot more control. It means you don\'t have to put all this information in the global prompt, but it also means you can customize your agent in a bit more detail. So, you can of'

[11:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'course set the the voice engine that you\'re using here. You can set things like background noise, all stuff you\'d usually expect. You can also add the prompt for things like behavior, tone, turn taking, all that sort of stuff. And you can also upload knowledge here. So,'

[11:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this to me just makes a bit more sense doing it this way, adding this information to your persona here. And then you can kind of connect those personas to the conversational pathway. So latency wise, Bland is very good. Unfortunately, they don\'t give you too'

[11:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much information on the exact latency, but if you kind of read between the lines and look at the time stamps between different steps, generally speaking in bland, I\'m getting between 450 and 650 milliseconds of latency, which is very good. Definitely puts'

[11:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Bland up there as one of the best tools. The best I\'ve seen on average is Vappy, which is about 514 milliseconds. So on a good day, Bland slightly beats that. On a less good day, it\'s a little bit below. Obviously, it\'s going to change'

[12:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'depending on things like models and the prompts you\'re using, but generally speaking, I\'ve not run into any latency issues with Bland. Now, let\'s talk about pricing. So, I believe pricing is not public on their website, but you can see'

[12:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it on their platform here. Generally speaking, it all kind of averages down to around about 12 cents per minute, 11 cents per minute, which is actually pretty reasonable. It\'s not the most affordable I\'ve seen. I\'d say the cheapest at the moment would be around'

[12:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about eight cents n cents per minute, but a lot of voice agent platforms average around about 14 15 cents per minute. And in terms of limits that you get around concurrency, they\'re all pretty reasonable as well. So for $300 a month, you\'ve got 50 concurrent call'

[12:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lines, which is pretty generous and that can be bumped up to virtually unlimited if you go up onto the enterprise plan. So both of these are great options for building voice agents on. And given that you can try both of them out for free, I\'d recommend doing that to see which'

[12:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one\'s going to be a better fit for your use case. Now, I\'ll drop links to both of them below, as well as the side-by-side comparison that I put together. And if you\'d like to watch me live build the same voice agent on both platforms, as well as four other voice AI tools, and then live test them with'

[13:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'real phone calls, you can check that video out'
